stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: MIFR 10063500
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description:
MIFR 10063500
This report contains preliminary analysis and is not intended to be a complete description of the submitted artifact's capabilities. Results may be incomplete due to the artifact's complexity or ability to defend against analysis techniques. If additional information is required, please contact the US-CERT Security Operations Center using the information at the end of this report.
US-CERT received an executable file. The file contained malicious code. The malware uses a domain generation algorithm to receive updates on the infected host. The malware tries to download several PHP files. The PHP files were not available for analysis.
Analysis Environment: 32_bit, windows_7000

stix:Indicator.indicator:Title: Malicious File Indicator
stix:Indicator.indicator:Description:
MIFR 10063500
The malware initiates a new instance of the Windows process svchost.exe and injects itself into it.
The malware uses a domain generation algorithm to receive updates on the infected host. Domain generation algorithm is when the malware creates thousands of domains such as www[.]magicmikesolutions[.]com, and tries to contact several of these domains with the intentions of receiving updates or commands.
The malware tries to download several PHP files. The PHP files were not available for analysis.
It drops a new instance of itself 67f7417e.exe into a new path: C:\Users\user01\AppData\Roaming\e3b0f7765
The malware then deletes the original copy.
No persistence was found when running the malware in a 64 bit Windows environment. Persistence was established by the malware in a 32 bit Windows environment with the creation of the following registry key:
HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run\4dfc3eb59 Data: C:\Documents and Settings\lab\Application Data\4dfc3eb59 \8e6879a1.exe
